Mithila / Madhubani tradition attribution
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Forge generates art INSPIRED BY the Madhubani (Mithila) painting tradition of
the Mithila region of Bihar, India. This is a living folk-art heritage,
practiced and carried forward primarily by women painters across generations,
and recognized in India by a Geographical Indication (GI) registration.
The tradition is studied and produced in several historically distinct
schools, including Bharni (filled-color), Kachni (line-only), Tantric, Godna
(tattoo-style), and Gobar (cow-dung-base) styles. Forge does not claim to be
authentic Madhubani painting, does not represent any practicing artist or
cooperative, and does not sell on behalf of any practitioner. Users who want
authentic work are strongly encouraged to commission or purchase directly
from practitioners and recognized cooperatives. See
docs/CULTURAL_HERITAGE_ATTRIBUTION.md for the full attribution statement.

